Philippe Balbiani, Andreas Herzig and Nicolas Troquard

Abstract

We propose two alternatives to Xuâ€™s axiomatization of the Chellas STIT. The first one also provides an alternative axiomatization of the deliberative STIT. The second one starts from the idea that the historic necessity operator can be defined as an abbreviation of operators of agency, and can thus be eliminated from the logic of the Chellas STIT. The second axiomatization also allows us to establish that the problem of deciding the satisfiability of a STITÂ formula without temporal operators is NP-complete in the single-agent case, and is NEXPTIME-complete in the multiagent case, both for the deliberative and the Chellasâ€™ STIT.

1 Introduction

STITÂ theory is one of the most prominent accounts of agency in philosophy of action. It is the logic of constructions of the form â€˜agent iğ‘–i sees to it that Ï†ğœ‘\varphi holdsâ€™. While STITÂ has played an important role in philosophical logic since the 80ies, it seems to be fair to say that its mathematical aspects have not been developed to the same extent. Most probably the reason is that STITâ€™s models of agency are much more complex than those existing for other modal concepts (such as say necessity, belief, or knowledge): first, the â€˜seeing-to-it-thatâ€™ modalities interact (or perhaps better: must be guaranteed not to interact) because the agentsâ€™ choices are supposed to be independent; second there is another kind of modality involved, viz.Â the â€˜master modalityâ€™ of historic necessity. There are also temporal modalities, but just as most of the other proof-theoretic approaches to STIT, we do not investigate these here.

As a consequence, proof systems for STITÂ are rather complex, too. To our knowledge the following have been proposed in the literature.

  • â€¢

    Xu provides Hilbert-style axiomatizations in terms of the historic necessity operator and Chellasâ€™ STITÂ operator [BPX01, Chap.Â 17], without considering temporal operators. As the deliberative STIT-operator can be expressed in terms of Chellasâ€™ (together with the historic necessity operator), the axiomatization transfers to the deliberative STIT. Xu proves their completeness (without considering the temporal dimension), by means of canonical models, and proves decidability by means of filtration. Besides, Xu also gives a complete axiomatization of the one-agent achievement STITÂ [BPX01, Chap.Â 16].

  • â€¢

    Wansing provides a tableau proof system for the deliberative STITÂ [Wan06]. The system is complete, but does not guarantee termination, and thus â€œis not tailored for defining tableau algorithmsâ€ [Wan06].

  • â€¢

    DÃ©gremont gives a dialogical proof procedure for the deliberative STITÂ [DÃ©g06]. Again, the system is complete, but does not guarantee termination, and can therefore only be used to build proofs by hand.

In this note, we focus on the so-called Chellas STITÂ named after his proponent [Che69, Che92]. The original operator defined by Chellas is nevertheless notably different since it does not come with the principle of independence of agents that plays a central role here. Following its presentation in [HB95], we use the term CSTITÂ to refer to the logic of that modal operator. We show that Xuâ€™s axiomatics of the logic of the Chellas STITÂ can be greatly simplified. After recalling it (Section 2) we propose an alternative one and prove its completeness (Section 3). Based on the latter we show that in presence of at least two agents, the modal operator of historic necessity can be defined as an abbreviation (Section 4). This leads to a simplified semantics (Section 5), and to characterizations of the complexity of satisfiability (Section 6).

6 Complexity

7 Conclusion

In this note we have established NEXPTIME-completeness of the satisfiability problem of formulas of Chellasâ€™ STITÂ and of the deliberative STITÂ for the case of two or more agents. All our complexity results appear to be new.

Our new axiom system for STITÂ of Section 3 is an interesting alternative to Xuâ€™s. It highlights the central role of the well-known equivalences [i]â€‹[j]â€‹Ï†â†”â–¡â€‹Ï†â†”delimited-[]ğ‘–delimited-[]ğ‘—ğœ‘â–¡ğœ‘[{i}][{j}]\varphi\leftrightarrow\Box\varphi and [iğ‘‘ğ‘ ğ‘¡ğ‘–ğ‘¡:[jğ‘‘ğ‘ ğ‘¡ğ‘–ğ‘¡:Ï†]]â†”âŠ¥[{i}\ \mathit{dstit}\!:{[{j}\ \mathit{dstit}\!:{\varphi}]}]\leftrightarrow\bot, for iâ‰ jğ‘–ğ‘—i\not=j in theories of agency: as we have shown, they allow to capture independence of agents just as Xuâ€™s schema (AIAk) does.

For the case of more than two agents, Section 4 provides a quite simple axiom system that is made up of very basic modal principles, and moreover, does without historic necessity.

As we have pointed out in Section 3, an alternative axiomatics for the deliberative STITÂ follows straightforwardly. We do not know whether the redundancy of historic necessity that we have established for the CSTITÂ in Section 4 transfers to the deliberative STIT.
